Adjusted EBITDA
We define Adjusted EBITDA as net income less income (loss) from discontinued operations, net of tax, and excluding
certain non‑GAAP adjustments, which the Company does not believe to be indicative of underlying business trends,
before interest expense, other non‑operating income (expense), net, income tax provision, and depreciation and
amortization expense. Adjusted EBITDA and adjusted EBITDA margin provide useful metrics for management to
assess operating performance. Margin is calculated for each period by dividing each line item by consolidated sales for
the respective period.
Below is a presentation of consolidated sales and a reconciliation of net income on a GAAP basis to adjusted EBITDA
and net income margin on a GAAP basis to adjusted EBITDA margin:
